{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "MethaneOxidation",
        "description": "Methane oxidation reaction-rate diagnostics from Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Ch. 6 §6.4, Table 6.1, pp. 219-227. Methane oxidation is the archetypal VOC oxidation mechanism in the troposphere, proceeding CH₄ → CH₃O₂ → CH₃O → HCHO → HCO → CO → CO₂. This observed-only algebraic component computes the 17 individual reaction rates R1-R17 of the complete Table 6.1 mechanism (10 bimolecular, 3 termolecular, 4 photolysis reactions) plus three diagnostic aggregates: the gross ozone production rate P_O3_gross = R15 + R3 (the two peroxy-radical + NO channels), the formaldehyde production rate P_HCHO = R6 + R8, and the methane loss rate L_CH4 = R1. Each reaction rate is the product of a 298 K rate constant and the reactant concentrations (R = k·[A]·[B] bimolecular, k·[M]·[A]·[B] termolecular, j·[A] photolysis). The fate of the methylperoxy radical CH₃O₂ — the O₃-producing NO channel R3 versus the chain-terminating HO₂ channel R4 — sets the ozone yield per CH₄ oxidized and is the central NOx-regime diagnostic of the mechanism. Purely algebraic (no time derivatives): 52 variables (15 input species and 17 rate constants encoded as parameters, 20 output diagnostics as state) and 20 equations. Migrated from GasChem.jl@8c12c048 src/methane_oxidation.jl:77 (`MethaneOxidation` @component).",
        "tags": [
            "gaschem",
            "methane-oxidation",
            "methane",
            "voc-oxidation",
            "tropospheric-chemistry",
            "ozone-production",
            "reaction-rates",
            "observed-only",
            "seinfeld-pandis"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "GasChem.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-xw55)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed. Wiley. Chapter 6 §6.4, Table 6.1, pp. 219-227. The complete methane oxidation mechanism — 17 reactions carrying CH₄ through CH₃O₂, CH₃O, HCHO, HCO and CO — with rate constants at 298 K. Rate constants from Table 6.1; HCHO + OH and HCHO photolysis values from p. 221."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "MethaneOxidation": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/methane_oxidation.jl:77\n\nUpstream `MethaneOxidation` is an MTK `@component` implementing the reaction-rate diagnostics of the complete methane oxidation mechanism — Table 6.1 of Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Chapter 6 §6.4, pp. 219-227. It declares 15 input-species `@variables` (CH4, CH3, CH3O2, CH3O, CH3OOH, HCHO, HCO, OH, HO2, H, NO, NO2, O, O2, M), 20 output-diagnostic `@variables` (the 17 reaction rates R1-R17 plus the three diagnostic aggregates P_O3_gross, P_HCHO, L_CH4), 17 rate-constant `@parameters`, and 20 algebraic equations, returning `System(eqs, t; name)`. The upstream tests compile it with `compile_with_inputs(sys, ch4_inputs)` (= `mtkcompile` with the 15 species as `inputs`) and solve the result as a `NonlinearProblem` with the inputs pinned to user-supplied concentrations. The companion `MethaneOxidationODE` `@component` at src/methane_oxidation.jl:213 is a separate Catalyst reaction-network ODE system and is migrated under its own bead (methane_ode.esm) — it is not part of this file.\n\nVariable-classification convention: the 15 input @variables are encoded here as `type: parameter` because they have no defining equation within the MethaneOxidation component itself — they are externally-supplied inputs that the upstream compile treats via `compile_with_inputs(...)`. The 17 rate constants are `type: parameter` as well. The 20 output @variables are `type: state` because each is the LHS of exactly one algebraic equation. This mirrors the rig-wide convention applied by the sibling gaschem diagnostic components ope.esm (5 input @variables encoded as parameters, 3 outputs as state) and oh_production.esm. The .esm therefore declares 52 variables = 32 `type: parameter` (15 species + 17 rate constants) + 20 `type: state`, and 20 entries in `equations`.\n\nStructural-test reproduction: the upstream `MethaneOxidation: Structural Verification` testitem (test/test_methane_oxidation.jl:4-35) asserts `length(unknowns(sys)) == 35`, `length(equations(sys)) == 20`, and `length(parameters(sys)) == 17`. The .esm preserves this exactly — the 35 upstream unknowns are the 20 `type: state` outputs plus the 15 input species (which upstream are unknowns, here `type: parameter`); the 17 upstream parameters are the 17 rate-constant `type: parameter` entries; and the 20 upstream equations are the 20 `equations` entries.\n\nRate-constant CGS→SI translation: Table 6.1 lists rate constants in CGS. The upstream Julia @parameters block converts them to SI — bimolecular rate coefficients are multiplied by 1e-6 (cm³/molec/s → m³/s) and termolecular ones by 1e-12 (cm⁶/molec²/s → m⁶/s) — and the .esm encodes the exact float64 each upstream expression produces:\n  k1   = 2.45e-12*exp(-1775/298)*1e-6 = 6.3437334324972315e-21 m^3/s\n  k3   = 7.7e-12*1e-6  = 7.699999999999999e-18 m^3/s\n  k4   = 5.2e-12*1e-6  = 5.199999999999999e-18 m^3/s\n  k5   = 3.5e-13*1e-6  = 3.5e-19 m^3/s\n  k6   = 1.9e-15*1e-6  = 1.9e-21 m^3/s\n  k7   = 3.6e-12*exp(200/298)*1e-6 = 7.043285735348479e-18 m^3/s\n  k8   = 1.9e-12*1e-6  = 1.9e-18 m^3/s\n  k10  = 9.0e-12*1e-6  = 9.0e-18 m^3/s\n  k13  = 5.2e-12*1e-6  = 5.199999999999999e-18 m^3/s\n  k15  = 8.1e-12*1e-6  = 8.1e-18 m^3/s\n  k2_0  = 1.0e-30*1e-12 = 1.0e-42 m^6/s\n  k14_0 = 5.7e-32*1e-12 = 5.7e-44 m^6/s\n  k17_0 = 6.0e-34*1e-12 = 6.0e-46 m^6/s\n  j9 = 5.0e-6, j11 = 3.0e-5, j12 = 4.0e-5, j16 = 8.0e-3 s^-1\nk1 and k7 carry an Arrhenius `exp` factor; MethaneOxidation has no temperature variable, so T is fixed at the 298 K reference and the two parameters reduce to compile-time constants — encoded as the exact float64 the upstream MTK @parameters block evaluates them to (computed in Julia 1.12 to bit-match upstream). The products k3, k4, k13 = X*1e-6 land exactly one ULP below the clean SI literals 7.7e-18 / 5.2e-18 / 5.2e-18 (the standard cm^3*1e-6 rounding artefact also noted in sibling ope.esm); they are encoded verbatim as the upstream product so the file's rate constants are bit-identical to upstream MTK. Every inline-test expected value below is computed from the .esm's own declared rate-constant and species literals, so the file is internally exact at rel=1e-10 regardless of the ULP-level CGS-product choice.\n\nObservability classification: this component is purely algebraic — every output is the LHS of one algebraic equation in the inputs, the rate constants, and (for L_CH4, P_HCHO, P_O3_gross) other outputs. No equation contains a `D(.)` operator, so the `(t)` index has no role and the trajectory is constant in time. Test and example scenarios use `time_span: [0.0, 1.0]` and sample at t=0, mirroring the convention of the sibling observed-only gaschem .esm files (ope.esm, oh_production.esm, gwp.esm).\n\nEquation cascade: the 20 equations form a topologically-ordered cascade — R1-R17 depend only on inputs and rate constants, while the three diagnostic aggregates depend on the R-states: L_CH4 ~ R1, P_HCHO ~ R6 + R8, P_O3_gross ~ R15 + R3. These three are written referencing the R-states rather than fully inlined, preserving the upstream symbolic structure (the diagnostic-sum identities the upstream tests assert) and mirroring the ope.esm / oh_production.esm cascade convention.\n\nNumerical defaults: the 15 input species carry no defaults upstream — the .esm defaults are the canonical upstream test scenario, the `input_vals` Dict reused across the MethaneOxidation testitems in test/test_methane_oxidation.jl (CH4=4.5e19, CH3=1e10, CH3O2=1e14, CH3O=1e10, CH3OOH=1e15, HCHO=1e16, HCO=1e10, OH=1e12, HO2=1e14, H=1e8, NO=2.5e15, NO2=2.5e16, O=1e8, O2=5.25e24, M=2.5e25, all in SI m^-3). At these defaults the methane-loss rate L_CH4 = R1 = 285468004462.3754 m^-3*s^-1 gives a CH4 chemical lifetime CH4/L_CH4 ~ 5.0 years, the gross ozone production rate P_O3_gross = 3.95e12 m^-3*s^-1, and the formaldehyde production rate P_HCHO ~ 9.98e13 m^-3*s^-1.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-10 / abs=1e-12): every equation is a small expression tree — the reaction rates are products of a rate constant and 2-3 concentrations (2-3 IEEE-754 multiplications), the diagnostics are one or two additions. Each output is correctly-rounded to within ~1-3 ULP ~ 1e-15 relative, leaving ~5 orders of magnitude of headroom under rel=1e-10 — far tighter than the upstream tests' own rtol bounds (0.01-0.1). The abs=1e-12 floor gates the boundary-case assertions (NO=0, OH=0, O2=0) where outputs collapse to exact IEEE-754 zero and the relative check is undefined. Matches sibling observed-only gaschem .esm tolerance: ope.esm rel=1e-10/abs=1e-12, oh_production.esm rel=1e-10/abs=1e-12.\n\nTests: 14 inline tests / 68 assertions. `upstream_default_scenario_all_reaction_rates` pins all 20 outputs at the canonical scenario and alone reproduces eight upstream testitems (Table 6.1 Rate Constants, R1, R3, P_HCHO=R6+R8, L_CH4=R1, P_O3_gross=R15+R3, Oxidation Chain Relative Rates, HCHO as Key Intermediate) plus All Reaction Rates Positive and CH4 Lifetime. `upstream_low_nox_regime` reproduces the Low NOx Regime testitem (R4 > R3); `upstream_r1_doubles_when_oh_doubled` reproduces R1 Scales Linearly with OH. Coverage beyond the upstream suite: per-input linearity tests (R1 in CH4, the peroxy+NO channels in NO, the termolecular rates in M, the CH3OOH reactions in CH3OOH), the quadratic CH3O2 self-reaction scaling, the high-NOx and pristine-low-OH regime endpoints, the docs formaldehyde-branching scenario, and three boundary-collapse tests (NO=0, OH=0, O2=0) that also verify the additive wiring of the P_HCHO and P_O3_gross diagnostic sums.\n\nExamples: 4 parameter-sweep examples with 7 plots — `ch3o2_radical_fate_vs_no` (NO log-sweep, the CH3O2 fate competition and gross O3 production, reproducing the docs `CH3O2 Fate` figure), `methane_sink_vs_oh` (OH log-sweep, the methane-loss / lifetime story), `formaldehyde_loss_pathways_vs_oh` (OH log-sweep, the HCHO branching analysis from the docs), and `gross_o3_production_no_ho2_heatmap` (joint 2-D NO*HO2 sweep of gross ozone production).\n\nUnit balance (verified): bimolecular rates R = k[m^3/s]*[m^-3]*[m^-3] = m^-3*s^-1; termolecular rates R = k[m^6/s]*[m^-3]*[m^-3]*[m^-3] = m^-3*s^-1; photolysis rates R = j[s^-1]*[m^-3] = m^-3*s^-1; the three diagnostic aggregates are sums of m^-3*s^-1 terms. All concentrations in SI m^-3, rate constants in SI m^3/s or m^6/s, photolysis frequencies in s^-1, all reaction rates and diagnostics in m^-3*s^-1. SI throughout; no unit conversion at parse or runtime."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-10,
                "abs": 1e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "k1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 6.3437334324972315e-21,
                    "description": "CH₄ + OH → CH₃ + H₂O rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 1, S&P §6.4). The methane-initiation step and the rate-limiting step of the entire oxidation chain — also the dominant tropospheric CH₄ sink. The upstream Julia default is the Arrhenius form 2.45e-12·exp(-1775/T)·1e-6 m³/s; because MethaneOxidation carries no temperature variable, T is fixed at the 298 K reference and the parameter evaluates to the constant 6.3437334324972315e-21 m³/s (encoded as the exact float64 the upstream @parameters block produces). The large activation energy of H-abstraction from the strong C-H bond makes this the slowest bimolecular rate constant in the mechanism."
                },
                "k3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 7.699999999999999e-18,
                    "description": "CH₃O₂ + NO → CH₃O + NO₂ rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 3). Upstream 7.7e-12 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 = 7.699999999999999e-18 m³/s (the CGS×1e-6 product lands one ULP below the clean literal 7.7e-18; encoded verbatim to bit-match upstream MTK). This is the O₃-producing fate of the methylperoxy radical — it converts NO to NO₂, whose photolysis yields O₃ — and is the high-NOx branch of the CH₃O₂ fate competition with reaction 4."
                },
                "k4": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 5.199999999999999e-18,
                    "description": "CH₃O₂ + HO₂ → CH₃OOH + O₂ rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 4). Upstream 5.2e-12 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 = 5.199999999999999e-18 m³/s (one ULP below the clean literal 5.2e-18; encoded verbatim). This is the chain-terminating fate of CH₃O₂ — it forms the relatively stable hydroperoxide CH₃OOH — and is the low-NOx branch of the CH₃O₂ fate competition with reaction 3."
                },
                "k5": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 3.5e-19,
                    "description": "CH₃O₂ + CH₃O₂ → products rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 5). Upstream 3.5e-13 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 = 3.5e-19 m³/s. The methylperoxy self-reaction; R5 = k5·[CH₃O₂]² is the only reaction rate quadratic in a single species. Negligible at moderate NOx but a radical sink when the CH₃O₂ pool is large and NO is scarce."
                },
                "k6": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 1.9e-21,
                    "description": "CH₃O + O₂ → HCHO + HO₂ rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 6). Upstream 1.9e-15 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 = 1.9e-21 m³/s. Converts the methoxy radical to formaldehyde while regenerating HO₂; one of the two HCHO production channels (the other is reaction 8)."
                },
                "k7": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 7.043285735348479e-18,
                    "description": "CH₃OOH + OH → CH₃O₂ + H₂O rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 5a). The upstream Julia default is the Arrhenius form 3.6e-12·exp(200/T)·1e-6 m³/s evaluated at the fixed 298 K reference, giving the constant 7.043285735348479e-18 m³/s (encoded as the exact upstream float64). The positive 200/T exponent gives a mild negative temperature dependence; this channel recycles the hydroperoxide back to methylperoxy."
                },
                "k8": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 1.9e-18,
                    "description": "CH₃OOH + OH → HCHO + OH + H₂O rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 5b). Upstream 1.9e-12 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 = 1.9e-18 m³/s. The OH-conserving branch of CH₃OOH + OH — OH is regenerated, so the net effect is CH₃OOH → HCHO; one of the two HCHO production channels."
                },
                "k10": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 9e-18,
                    "description": "HCHO + OH → HCO + H₂O rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 10, S&P p. 221). Upstream 9.0e-12 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 = 9.0e-18 m³/s. The OH-driven formaldehyde-loss channel; competes with the two HCHO photolysis channels (reactions 11 and 12)."
                },
                "k13": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 5.199999999999999e-18,
                    "description": "HCO + O₂ → CO + HO₂ rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 13). Upstream 5.2e-12 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 = 5.199999999999999e-18 m³/s (one ULP below the clean literal 5.2e-18; encoded verbatim). Converts the formyl radical to carbon monoxide — the penultimate carbon product of the chain CH₄ → … → CO → CO₂ — while regenerating HO₂."
                },
                "k15": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 8.1e-18,
                    "description": "HO₂ + NO → OH + NO₂ rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 15). Upstream 8.1e-12 cm³/molec/s × 1e-6 = 8.1e-18 m³/s. The central HOx-cycle propagation step: it regenerates OH (sustaining the catalytic oxidation chain) and converts NO to NO₂, the second of the two peroxy+NO channels that feed gross O₃ production."
                },
                "k2_0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^6/s",
                    "default": 1e-42,
                    "description": "CH₃ + O₂ + M → CH₃O₂ + M termolecular rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 2). Upstream 1.0e-30 cm⁶/molec²/s × 1e-12 (the cm⁶ → m⁶ conversion factor for termolecular rate coefficients) = 1.0e-42 m⁶/s. The third body M carries away the excess energy of the nascent CH₃O₂ adduct."
                },
                "k14_0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^6/s",
                    "default": 5.7e-44,
                    "description": "H + O₂ + M → HO₂ + M termolecular rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 14). Upstream 5.7e-32 cm⁶/molec²/s × 1e-12 = 5.7e-44 m⁶/s. Converts the hydrogen atom released by HCHO photolysis (reaction 11) into HO₂."
                },
                "k17_0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^6/s",
                    "default": 6e-46,
                    "description": "O + O₂ + M → O₃ + M termolecular rate constant (Table 6.1 reaction 17). Upstream 6.0e-34 cm⁶/molec²/s × 1e-12 = 6.0e-46 m⁶/s. The ozone-forming step — the O atom liberated by NO₂ photolysis (reaction 16) recombines with O₂."
                },
                "j9": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 5e-06,
                    "description": "CH₃OOH + hν → CH₃O + OH photolysis frequency (Table 6.1 reaction 9). Upstream default 5.0e-6 s⁻¹, a representative clear-sky daytime value. The photolytic loss channel of methyl hydroperoxide."
                },
                "j11": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 3e-05,
                    "description": "HCHO + hν → HCO + H photolysis frequency (Table 6.1 reaction 11). Upstream default 3.0e-5 s⁻¹. The radical (H-atom-producing) channel of formaldehyde photolysis — a net HOx source after H + O₂ + M → HO₂."
                },
                "j12": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 4e-05,
                    "description": "HCHO + hν → H₂ + CO photolysis frequency (Table 6.1 reaction 12, S&P p. 221). Upstream default 4.0e-5 s⁻¹. The molecular (radical-free) channel of formaldehyde photolysis; j12 > j11 so the molecular channel slightly outpaces the radical channel at the reference photolysis rates."
                },
                "j16": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 0.008,
                    "description": "NO₂ + hν → NO + O photolysis frequency (Table 6.1 reaction 16). Upstream default 8.0e-3 s⁻¹, the fastest photolysis in the mechanism. Liberates the O atom that reaction 17 converts to O₃ — the photolytic engine of tropospheric ozone formation."
                },
                "CH4": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 4.5e+19,
                    "description": "Methane (CH₄) number density [m⁻³]. The chain-initiating species; the most abundant atmospheric hydrocarbon (~1.8 ppm). Default 4.5e19 m⁻³ (~1800 ppb at STP) is the canonical upstream test scenario value. Appears only in reaction 1 (R1 = k1·CH₄·OH) and hence sets the CH₄-loss rate L_CH4."
                },
                "CH3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 10000000000.0,
                    "description": "Methyl radical (CH₃) number density [m⁻³]. The first chain intermediate, produced by R1 and consumed by R2 (CH₃ + O₂ + M). Default 1.0e10 m⁻³ — a short-lived radical, present only in trace amounts."
                },
                "CH3O2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 100000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Methylperoxy radical (CH₃O₂) number density [m⁻³]. The pivotal branch-point intermediate: its fate splits between the O₃-producing NO channel (R3), the chain-terminating HO₂ channel (R4), and self-reaction (R5). Default 1.0e14 m⁻³."
                },
                "CH3O": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 10000000000.0,
                    "description": "Methoxy radical (CH₃O) number density [m⁻³]. Produced by R3 and R9; consumed by R6 (CH₃O + O₂ → HCHO + HO₂). Default 1.0e10 m⁻³."
                },
                "CH3OOH": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1000000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Methyl hydroperoxide (CH₃OOH) number density [m⁻³]. The chain-terminating product of R4; reprocessed by R7, R8 and photolysis R9. Default 1.0e15 m⁻³."
                },
                "HCHO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1e+16,
                    "description": "Formaldehyde (HCHO) number density [m⁻³]. The key carbon intermediate of the chain, with three loss channels: R10 (OH), R11 (radical photolysis) and R12 (molecular photolysis). Default 1.0e16 m⁻³."
                },
                "HCO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 10000000000.0,
                    "description": "Formyl radical (HCO) number density [m⁻³]. Produced by R10 and R11; consumed by R13 (HCO + O₂ → CO + HO₂). Default 1.0e10 m⁻³."
                },
                "OH": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Hydroxyl radical (OH) number density [m⁻³]. The primary atmospheric oxidant; drives R1, R7, R8 and R10. Default 1.0e12 m⁻³ (~1e6 molec/cm³), the canonical daytime tropospheric value. R1, R7, R8, R10 and the diagnostic L_CH4 are all exactly linear in OH."
                },
                "HO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 100000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Hydroperoxyl radical (HO₂) number density [m⁻³]. Drives the chain-terminating R4 and the O₃-producing R15 (HO₂ + NO). Default 1.0e14 m⁻³ (~1e8 molec/cm³)."
                },
                "H": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 100000000.0,
                    "description": "Hydrogen atom (H) number density [m⁻³]. Released by HCHO radical photolysis (R11); consumed by R14 (H + O₂ + M → HO₂). Default 1.0e8 m⁻³ — an extremely short-lived radical."
                },
                "NO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2500000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Nitric oxide (NO) number density [m⁻³]. The NOx species that switches the chain between its O₃-producing and chain-terminating regimes. Drives R3 and R15, so both peroxy+NO channels — and hence P_O3_gross — are exactly linear in NO. Default 2.5e15 m⁻³ (~0.1 ppb at STP)."
                },
                "NO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e+16,
                    "description": "Nitrogen dioxide (NO₂) number density [m⁻³]. Appears only in reaction 16 (R16 = j16·NO₂, NO₂ photolysis). Default 2.5e16 m⁻³ (~1 ppb at STP)."
                },
                "O": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 100000000.0,
                    "description": "Oxygen atom (O) number density [m⁻³]. Liberated by NO₂ photolysis (R16); consumed by R17 (O + O₂ + M → O₃). Default 1.0e8 m⁻³."
                },
                "O2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 5.25e+24,
                    "description": "Molecular oxygen (O₂) number density [m⁻³]. The bath-gas oxidant; a factor in R2, R6, R13, R14 and R17. Default 5.25e24 m⁻³ (the ~21% O₂ fraction of STP air number density)."
                },
                "M": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e+25,
                    "description": "Total air number density (M) [m⁻³]. The third body in the three termolecular reactions R2, R14 and R17, each of which is exactly linear in M. Default 2.5e25 m⁻³ (STP)."
                },
                "R1": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 1, CH₄ + OH → CH₃ + H₂O [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R1 = k1·CH₄·OH. The methane-initiation rate; equals the CH₄-loss rate L_CH4. At the default scenario R1 ≈ 2.85e11 m⁻³·s⁻¹."
                },
                "R2": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 2, CH₃ + O₂ + M → CH₃O₂ + M [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R2 = k2_0·M·CH₃·O₂. Termolecular — exactly linear in the air density M."
                },
                "R3": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 3, CH₃O₂ + NO → CH₃O + NO₂ [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R3 = k3·CH₃O₂·NO. The O₃-producing fate of methylperoxy; at the default scenario R3 = 1.925e12 m⁻³·s⁻¹ and dominates R4 by a factor ~37 (the moderate-to-high-NOx regime)."
                },
                "R4": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 4, CH₃O₂ + HO₂ → CH₃OOH + O₂ [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R4 = k4·CH₃O₂·HO₂. The chain-terminating fate of methylperoxy; overtakes R3 only in the low-NOx regime."
                },
                "R5": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 5, CH₃O₂ + CH₃O₂ → products [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R5 = k5·CH₃O₂·CH₃O₂. The methylperoxy self-reaction — the only rate quadratic in a single species, so R5 scales as CH₃O₂²."
                },
                "R6": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 6, CH₃O + O₂ → HCHO + HO₂ [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R6 = k6·CH₃O·O₂. Converts the methoxy radical to formaldehyde; one of the two formaldehyde-production channels summed into P_HCHO."
                },
                "R7": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 7, CH₃OOH + OH → CH₃O₂ + H₂O [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R7 = k7·CH₃OOH·OH. Recycles the hydroperoxide back to methylperoxy."
                },
                "R8": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 8, CH₃OOH + OH → HCHO + OH + H₂O [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R8 = k8·CH₃OOH·OH. The OH-conserving branch of CH₃OOH + OH; the second formaldehyde-production channel summed into P_HCHO."
                },
                "R9": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 9, CH₃OOH + hν → CH₃O + OH [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R9 = j9·CH₃OOH. Photolytic loss of methyl hydroperoxide."
                },
                "R10": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 10, HCHO + OH → HCO + H₂O [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R10 = k10·HCHO·OH. The OH-driven formaldehyde-loss channel — the only HCHO-loss channel that depends on OH."
                },
                "R11": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 11, HCHO + hν → HCO + H [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R11 = j11·HCHO. The radical (H-atom-producing) channel of formaldehyde photolysis."
                },
                "R12": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 12, HCHO + hν → H₂ + CO [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R12 = j12·HCHO. The molecular (radical-free) channel of formaldehyde photolysis; R12 > R11 at the reference photolysis rates since j12 > j11."
                },
                "R13": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 13, HCO + O₂ → CO + HO₂ [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R13 = k13·HCO·O₂. Converts the formyl radical to carbon monoxide."
                },
                "R14": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 14, H + O₂ + M → HO₂ + M [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R14 = k14_0·M·H·O₂. Termolecular — exactly linear in M."
                },
                "R15": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 15, HO₂ + NO → OH + NO₂ [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R15 = k15·HO₂·NO. The HOx-cycle propagation step; the second peroxy+NO channel summed into P_O3_gross."
                },
                "R16": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 16, NO₂ + hν → NO + O [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R16 = j16·NO₂. NO₂ photolysis — liberates the O atom that R17 converts to ozone."
                },
                "R17": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Rate of reaction 17, O + O₂ + M → O₃ + M [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: R17 = k17_0·M·O·O₂. Termolecular — exactly linear in M; the ozone-forming step."
                },
                "P_O3_gross": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Gross ozone production rate [m⁻³·s⁻¹] (S&P Eq. 6.9 analog): P_O3_gross = R15 + R3, the sum of the two peroxy-radical + NO channels. Each HO₂ + NO and CH₃O₂ + NO reaction converts an NO to an NO₂ whose photolysis yields one O₃, so this is the gross rate at which the methane mechanism makes ozone. Exactly linear in NO."
                },
                "P_HCHO": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Formaldehyde production rate [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: P_HCHO = R6 + R8, the sum of the CH₃O + O₂ channel (R6) and the OH-conserving CH₃OOH + OH channel (R8)."
                },
                "L_CH4": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Methane loss rate [m⁻³·s⁻¹]: L_CH4 = R1. The only CH₄ sink in the mechanism is reaction with OH, so the methane loss rate equals R1 exactly. The CH₄ chemical lifetime is CH₄ / L_CH4; at the default scenario this is ~5.0 years, consistent with the observed tropospheric methane lifetime."
                }
            },
